title: For Sale:  Thompson Tommy & 1911 100th Anniversary of Chicago Typewriter Boxed Set
postcontent: Thompson Tommy & 1911 100th Anniversary of Chicago Typewriter Boxed SetNumber 22 or 1500 ProducedOne Thompson Tommy Gun + One Thompson 1911 PistolWith Engraving - A Once In A Lifetime ChanceDon't Miss Out On This One VISIT OUR WEBSITE REGISTER TO WIN FREE GUN    A boxed set for the Tommy Gun’s 100th anniversary. (Photo: Auto-Ordnance)  Auto-Ordnance is offering a boxed set of two classics, the Chicago Typewriter, AKA Tommy Gun, and a 1911A1 pistol, in observation of the Tommy Gun’s 100-year anniversary. Though the .45 ACP semi-auto Chicago Typewriter is renowned for showing up in the hands of Prohibition-era gangsters, the new release highlights earlier history of the firearm, which pre-dates U.S. involvement in World War I. The faithful reproductions, finished in blued steel and walnut, come boxed together in a hard case bearing the “Chicago Typewriter” and Thompson logos. Both guns are stamped with the Thompson bullet logo. They’re sold only as a set; MSRP $1,971. This is a limited edition of 1,500. The Thompson sub-machine gun, designed first as a tool for clearing enemy trenches, was the brainchild of John T. Thompson, a West Point graduate originally from Newport, Kentucky. In the Army, Thompson studied engineering and artillery, and took an interest in small arms design. After retiring from the Army and entering employment as Chief Engineer at Remington Arms, Thompson designed the platform in 1916. He re-enlisted when the U.S. became involved in the war, eventually being promoted to Brigadier General. Thompson perfected the design after the war’s end, and was awarded a patent in 1920. By then, military applications were mostly moot, so he marketed the gun to police agencies and in the civilian market. Thompson never lived to see his design fulfill its intended use. Shortly after his 1940 death at age 79, the U.S. Army placed large orders for Thompson submachine guns for the World War II effort. postcontent: size / dimensions: 4x8Up for sale / trade is this work / utility trailer. It was left over by the previous owner after a move. It has a 4x8 box, as you can see in the pictures. There's also a smaller bottom section that looks like it would be perfect for hauling lumber and project wood. The top section floor / bottom section ceiling seems to bolt out in case you want to remove it to haul larger cargo.On the sides of the trailer, it has two side access doors equipped with two lift arms for each. Or as Elon Musk of Telsa would call them "falcon wing doors". This makes side access a breeze. It also has vents installed on the top front corners of the trailer for ventilation on those hot summer days. Around the front side the spare tire is mounted above the tongue. Trailer has chains, third wheel, and light connection at the front of tongue. I have not tested the lights but I will continue to clean it up this weekend.On the roof, there is a built in ladder rack with pvc rollers that make loading/unloading ladders a breeze. I also just finished up taring the roof with wet-stick roof cement for waterproofness. It's drying in the barn right now and curing up.Trailer is equipped with adequate reflectors per Michigan law, has mud flaps and rock guard along the back side (see pictures) and fenders are in good shape. Tires are in good shape as well. Trailer is currently untitled as it's a homebuilt and I'm going to continue working on it this weekend doing various other touch-ups.
